2 NEEDFINDING PLAN
2.1 Overview
To inform the redesign of the airline mobile boarding pass, I will conduct two needfinding activities. Together, these activities will reveal how real users cur- rently experience the interface and identify specific design violations that can guide early ideation.
2.2 Activity 1: User Survey
Goal: To understand how travelers interact with their mobile boarding pass at different stages of the airport journey, what information they find most critical at each stage, and where they experience confusion or friction.
Participants: The target is approximately 30 participants. Participants will be recruited from two sources: (1) Georgia Tech OMSCS classmates via the Ed discussion post, and (2) personal and professional contacts who travel by air at least once per year. No specific demographic restrictions will be applied.
Recruitment: The survey will be distributed via a peersurvey shared through course communication channels and personal messaging. An introductory note will explain the research purpose and confirm that participation is anonymous.
Survey Structure: The survey will take approximately 5 minutes to complete and will include the following sections:
• Background: Travel frequency, airline app usage and familiarity.
• Stage-by-stage experience: For each of three stages (security, gate, boarding), par- ticipants will be asked what information they look for, how easy it is to find,
and whether they have experienced any confusion or delay.
• Info overload: Likert-scale questions about cognitive load and visual clutter.
• Open-ended feedback: What they wish the boarding pass showed differently, and
any specific frustrations or positive experiences they recall.
The full question text is included in Appendix A.
2.3 Activity 2: Heuristic Evaluation
Goal: To systematically identify usability violations in an existing airline mobile boarding pass interface using established heuristics.
2

Target Interface: The evaluation will focus on the Delta Air Lines mobile app boarding pass screen, accessed via a personal account with an upcoming or recently completed flight. Delta is one of the most widely used airline apps in the United States and is representative of the current industry standard for mobile boarding pass design.
Figure 1—Delta Mobile Boarding Pass
Heuristics: Three heuristics will be applied, drawn from Nielsen’s Ten Usability
Heuristics:
1. Match Between System and the Real World (Nielsen Heuristic #2) The system should use language and concepts familiar to the user, and information should appear in a natural and logical order. Evaluation question: Does the boarding pass present information in the order and priority that reflects how a traveler actually moves through the airport?
2. Recognition Rather Than Recall (Nielsen Heuristic #6) Users should not have to remember information from one part of the interface to another. Minimizing the user’s memory load means making relevant objects, actions, and options
 3

visible. Evaluation question: At each stage of travel, is the most contextually
relevant information immediately visible without scanning or scrolling?
3. Aesthetic and Minimalist Design (Nielsen Heuristic #8) Every extra unit of information in a dialogue competes with relevant information and diminishes its relative visibility. Evaluation question: Does the boarding pass display only what is necessary, or does it present extraneous information that increases
cognitive load?
Evaluation Process I will evaluate the interface independently by walking through the three airport stages (security, gate, seat) while referencing the boarding pass screen, noting where each heuristic is obeyed or violated, and assigning a severity rating (0–4) to each identified issue following Nielsen’s severity scale. Findings will be documented in a structured table in Appendix B.
3 NEEDFINDING RESULTS
User Survey: The survey was distributed via the Georgia Tech OMSCS Ed Dis- cussion board and personal contacts, hosted on the PeerSurvey platform. A total of 38 responses were collected. The sample skewed toward experienced mobile boarding pass users: 66% had used mobile passes for three or more years, and the participant pool included users of Delta, United, American, Southwest, mo- bile wallet, and a range of international apps (KLM, Emirates, JetBlue, DigiYatra, and others). Ages skewed toward 18–29 (55%).
Key results by stage: At security, 66% of respondents looked first for the bar- code/QR code; 58% found it "somewhat easy" to locate, while 32% reported difficulty or were neutral. At the gate, gate number (76%) and boarding time (74%) were the top-cited information needs, but only 5% found gate-stage infor- mation immediately visible — 29% reported difficulty or were neutral, making the gate the highest-friction stage. After boarding, 87% needed only their seat number. Across all stages, 55% of respondents reported either a near-miss or stress while searching for information. Design preference was decisive: 87% se- lected a stage-aware simplified view as their top desired improvement, and 89% rated context-aware highlighting as useful or extremely useful.
Heuristic Evaluation: The evaluation was conducted as planned using the Delta Android app boarding pass, walking through the security, gate, and boarding stages and evaluating against three Nielsen heuristics. The full findings table is
4

in Appendix B.
Match Between System and the Real World (H2): Partially obeyed. The barcode is positioned at the top (appropriate for security) but below it, the layout does not reflect the sequential journey. Gate number, boarding time, seat, zone, and confirmation details are displayed with similar visual weight regardless of travel stage, with no correspondence to the traveler’s real-world progression. Severity 3 (major) for the absence of any stage-aware hierarchy across the full card.
Recognition Rather Than Recall (H6): Violated at the gate and boarding stages. The boarding group/zone label is small and non-dominant; a traveler who hears their zone called must search the card to confirm it. After boarding, seat number is not surfaced as the primary element. QR code, status badges, and flight details continue to compete for visual attention. Severity 3 at the gate, Severity 2 at boarding.
Aesthetic and Minimalist Design (H8): Consistently violated. The boarding pass displays more than fifteen simultaneous elements including confirmation number, medallion status, three status badges (SkyPriority, TSA Pre, DIGITAL ID), Apple Wallet button, on-time indicator, and a "Where’s My Plane?" link. The majority of which are irrelevant to the user’s current task at every stage evaluated. Severity 3–4.
Severity: 0 = none; 1 = cosmetic; 2 = minor; 3 = major; 4 = catastrophic.
3.1 Key Insights
Insight 1 — Information needs per stage are far narrower than the interface assumes. The survey confirmed what was only suspected: at security, one item dominates (barcode, 66%); at boarding, one item is needed (seat number, 87%). Yet the heuristic evaluation found more than fifteen elements competing for attention at every stage. The interface is designed for completeness when users need precision.
Insight 2 — The gate stage is the highest-friction point, not security. Prior to needfinding, security seemed like the most stressful stage. The data reversed this assumption: 11% found security information immediately visible vs. only 5% at the gate; 29% experienced gate-stage friction vs. 32% at security and the gate involves active listening for a boarding zone call, compounding the cost of any search delay. The heuristic evaluation rated gate violations at Severity 3 on two
