Insight 3 — Users want dynamic prioritization, not less information. 47% de- scribed the overall information quantity as "about right," yet 55% reported stress or near-misses and 87% requested a stage-aware view. The resolution came from the Q11 write-in response selected by 32% of respondents: "apt info included, but highlighted info differs with each app." Users are not overwhelmed by the con- tent. They are frustrated that emphasis does not shift with context. The design target is dynamic prioritization, not content reduction.
4 INITIAL BRAINSTORMING PLAN
The brainstorming phase builds on three confirmed insights from needfinding: information needs are narrowly stage-specific, the gate is the highest-friction stage, and users want dynamic prioritization rather than reduced content. The session is conducted individually with Claude as an AI ideation partner, follow- ing course principles of deferred judgment, quantity before quality, and breadth before convergence.
The session uses four structured turns: (1) generate at least 8 concepts spanning conservative visual redesign to novel interaction paradigms, with a boarding time countdown element required somewhere in the space; (2) deepen the three
6

highest-potential concepts with specific UI details; (3) a devil’s advocate round to surface assumptions and overlooked users; (4) synthesize into three distinct prototypable alternatives. The full transcript is Appendix C.
Bias Mitigation
• Fixation bias — countered by requiring gestural and voice concepts in Turn 1
before any refinement, forcing exploration beyond the current card layout.
• Frequency bias — countered by making international travelers, first-time flyers,
and accessibility needs the explicit focus of Turn 3.
• Solutionism bias — countered by structuring selection only after the devil’s
advocate turn has introduced friction into the most appealing ideas.
5 BRAINSTORMING RESULTS
5.1 5.1 Overview of Activity
The session ran across four turns with Claude as AI partner. Turn 1 produced 8 concepts ranging from double-tap zoom gestures to ambient lock screen wid- gets, with the boarding countdown integrated as a depleting arc or countdown bar rather than a numeric ticker. Turn 2 deepened Stage Spotlight, Swipe-Stage Cards, and Ambient Color + Timer Ring with concrete interaction details. Turn 3 surfaced six counterarguments, two of which introduced considerations absent from the initial generation: the need for gate-change alerting within stage-aware interfaces, and the risk that a visible countdown increases anxiety for stressed travelers. Turn 4 synthesized three alternatives with distinct paradigms. The full transcript is in Appendix B.
5.2 Ideas Generated
Automated / Time-Aware
• Stage Spotlight — Focus panel auto-promotes 1–2 critical fields by stage. Gate view: boarding time with depleting arc, zone in 72pt bold. All other details in a collapsible drawer.
• Ambient Color + Timer Ring — Background shifts by stage (navy → amber → green). At the gate, a large circular arc surrounds boarding time and depletes as boarding approaches. Zone is the second-largest element.
7

• Lock Screen Live Card — Persistent lock screen widget showing one field at a time: barcode thumbnail → gate + countdown bar → seat number. No app required.
User-Controlled
• Swipe-Stage Cards — Three labeled swipeable cards; each with a hero field (72pt), supporting field, and fine-print strip. Gate card: zone as hero, boarding time + slim countdown bar as supporting. Auto-selected by time, fully manual- override via tabs.
• Progressive Disclosure Pass — Opens at barcode only. One tap: gate view with boarding time and zone. Two taps: full card. Purely additive.
Gesture / Voice
• Double-Tap Zoom — Double-tap any field to expand it full-screen. Swipe
down to dismiss. Enhancement on any layout.
• Gesture-Driven Stages — Swipe up to advance stage, swipe down to go back. Long-press to expand any field full-screen. All navigation gestural.
• Voice-Activated Pass — “What’s my boarding zone?” Answer spoken and shown in large text. Visual display is the fallback.
Added in Devil’s Advocate Turn
• Gate-Change Alert Layer — Any stage-aware interface needs a non-modal gate-change signal (amber flash + updated gate number) regardless of current view.
• Anxiety-Aware Timer Mode — Countdown visibility made opt-in; default shows boarding time as a static label. Depleting arc enabled in settings.
5.3 Selected Design Alternatives
Three alternatives selected for prototyping, each addressing gate friction with a
distinct interaction paradigm:
• Stage Spotlight — selected because it directly serves the 89% who rated context-aware automation as useful or extremely useful. No navigation required for the most common case.
8

• Three-Card Pass — selected to serve the 32% who distrust hidden information. Full manual control via labeled tabs, nothing ever hidden, while enforcing strong visual hierarchy within each card.
• Ambient Pass — selected because it reaches travelers who never open the app, screenshotters, mobile wallet users, low-battery scenarios, meeting users at their actual behavior.
5.4 Textual Prototypes
Alternative 1 — Stage Spotlight (Automated Progressive Disclosure)
When the traveler opens the app at security, the QR code fills the upper two- thirds of the screen in a clean high-contrast panel with no competing text; a collapsed one-line drawer below reads “Seat 12A · Gate A18 · 6:35 AM” and expands on tap. As the flight timeline advances the panel transitions to Gate view: boarding time appears in 32pt type with a slim depleting arc beneath it. A peripheral urgency cue that empties as boarding approaches without displaying a ticking number and the zone identifier fills the center in 72pt bold. If a gate change occurs, the panel header flashes amber once and the new gate number pulses briefly. After boarding, the panel surfaces seat number in 80pt type with row and cabin in fine print below. A persistent “See all details” link at the bottom of every view provides one-tap access to the full card at any time.
Alternative 2 — Three-Card Pass (Explicit User-Controlled Navigation)
The boarding pass is structured as three labeled swipeable cards. Security, Gate, Boarding navigable via tabs at the top or horizontal swipe. The Security card shows the QR code at 70% of screen height with passenger name and flight number in fine print below. The Gate card enforces a strict hierarchy: zone in 72pt bold as the hero element; boarding time in 28pt type with a slim horizontal countdown bar directly beneath it as the supporting field; gate number, terminal, and status in a fine-print strip at the bottom. The Boarding card shows seat number in 80pt type centered on screen with a seat-map icon below. The active card is auto-selected by time, signaled by a highlighted tab, but the traveler can tap or swipe to any card at any moment. Nothing is ever more than one interaction away.
Alternative 3 — Ambient Pass (Persistent Lock Screen + Widget Presence)
9

The Ambient Pass lives as a dynamic home screen widget and lock screen Live Activity, surfacing one contextual field at all times without opening the app. At check-in, a one-tap prompt adds the widget. At security: QR thumbnail with passenger name. At the gate: a compact chip showing gate number and boarding time with a slim countdown bar, readable on the lock screen without unlocking; a brief amber border flash signals any gate change. After the boarding group is called: seat number in 48pt type as the sole element. Tapping anywhere opens the full boarding pass. For travelers who screenshotted their pass or use mobile wallet, the widget delivers dynamic gate and countdown information that static screenshots cannot, meeting users at their actual behavior.
