STUDENT
Play devil’s advocate. What assumptions might lead us astray — think about users who distrust automation, accessibility needs, international travelers, gate changes, or travelers who never open the app.
CLAUDE (AI)
Several worth examining:
Stage transitions may not be clean. A gate change at T-15, a delay, or secondary screening scrambles time-based models. A design that has already advanced to Gate view must surface gate changes prominently — otherwise it actively misleads the traveler.
Many travelers never open the app. Screenshotters, mobile wallet users, and low-battery travelers won’t benefit from any in-app feature. The countdown and stage-aware logic only help if the design also works as a widget or lock screen presence.
Infrequent flyers may distrust hidden information. Users who fly 1–2 times per year may panic when their confirmation number isn’t immediately visible. Any design that collapses information needs a clearly labeled escape hatch.
Countdown arcs can increase anxiety. A visibly depleting ring may heighten stress for anxious travelers. Making the countdown opt-in rather than always-on is worth considering.
Gestural navigation has accessibility barriers. Swipe-up-to-advance and long- press patterns require motor ability and learned behavior. Every gesture needs a tap-based equivalent.
Voice fails in loud environments. Airports are noisy. A voice interface that mis- hears “Zone 3” in a crowded terminal makes the problem worse. Voice should
18

be an enhancement, never the only path.
