9 INITIAL PROTOTYPING
9.1 Alternative 1: Stage Spotlight (Automated Progressive Disclosure)
Description: This prototype uses a single, dynamic panel that auto-promotes information based on the traveler’s stage. It relies on automation to reduce cognitive load while providing a manual "escape hatch" for secondary information.
Prototype Image: [See Figure 2 in Appendix D]
Rationale: This design is rooted in Nielsen’s Heuristic #8 (Aesthetic and Minimalist Design) by suppressing irrelevant fields. It leverages automation to meet the 89% of survey respondents who requested context-aware highlighting. By using a depleting arc for the countdown, it provides a peripheral urgency cue (Recognition over Recall, H6) without the stress of a ticking numeric clock.

9.2 Alternative 2: Three-Card Pass (Explicit User-Controlled Navigation)
Description: A structured interface consisting of three labeled, swipeable cards: Security, Gate, and Boarding. Each card enforces a strict visual hierarchy with a "hero" field.
Prototype Image: [See Figure 3 in Appendix D]
Rationale: This alternative prioritizes Nielsen’s Heuristic #3 (User Control and Freedom) and Heuristic #1 (Visibility of System Status). It serves the 32% of users who expressed a need for all info to be present but better highlighted. The horizontal swipe paradigm maps the digital interface to the sequential, real-world journey (H2: Match between System and the Real World).

9.3 Alternative 3: Ambient Pass (Lock Screen + Widget Presence)
Description: A non-app interface that leverages OS-level widgets and Live Activities to surface one contextual field at a time directly on the lock screen.
Prototype Image: [See Figure 4 in Appendix D]
Rationale: This design addresses the interaction cost of repeatedly unlocking a phone and navigating to an app. It is rooted in the principle of "meeting users where they are," specifically targeting the 45% of respondents who primarily use mobile wallets. It minimizes memory load by ensuring the most critical information is always visible (H6: Recognition rather than Recall).

