11 PROTOTYPE EVALUATION
11.1 Evaluation Methodology
The three low-fidelity prototypes were evaluated against the primary needs identified in the needfinding phase: reducing cognitive load at the gate, providing dynamic prioritization, and ensuring the right information is visible at the right stage. Evaluation was conducted using a walkthrough of the three airport stages (security, gate, boarding) while referencing the design goals and Nielsen’s heuristics.

11.2 Evaluation of Alternative 1: Stage Spotlight
Strengths: This design most effectively addresses the "information overload" problem (H8) by suppressing 80% of the typical boarding pass clutter. By promoting the boarding zone and time at the gate stage, it directly tackles the highest-friction point identified in Insight 2. The depleting arc provides a non-numeric urgency cue that reduces anxiety while maintaining awareness (H6).
Weaknesses: The primary risk is the "Black Box" effect. If the automated transition fails (e.g., due to a delay or gate change not syncing), the user may find it difficult to trust the system. The "See all details" escape hatch is a critical mitigation for Heuristic #3 (User Control).

11.3 Evaluation of Alternative 2: Three-Card Pass
Strengths: This alternative provides the strongest sense of user control and freedom (H3). It eliminates the fear of "missing" information because all cards are always accessible. The clear mapping to the sequential airport journey (Security -> Gate -> Boarding) provides a natural mental model (H2).
Weaknesses: Compared to the Stage Spotlight, it requires more active interaction. A traveler juggling luggage and a phone may find swiping or tapping tabs slightly more burdensome than a zero-interaction automated view. However, it serves the 32% of survey respondents who prefer seeing everything over automated filtering.

11.4 Evaluation of Evaluation of Alternative 3: Ambient Pass
Strengths: This design has the lowest interaction cost. By surfacing information on the lock screen, it eliminates the need to unlock the phone, find the app, and wait for it to load—a major benefit during high-stress moments like the security line (H6). It effectively reaches the 45% of users who rely on mobile wallets.
Weaknesses: Space constraints on the lock screen limit the ability to provide context or "fine print." It works best as a companion to a full pass rather than a standalone replacement. It also faces the same automation risks as the Stage Spotlight regarding accurate stage transitions.

11.5 Summary of Findings
While all three alternatives significantly improve upon the current industry standard (Delta app), the Stage Spotlight is the most promising for the majority of users (89% preference). The Three-Card Pass serves as a robust alternative for those who prioritize control. The final design should likely integrate the "Ambient" features as a system-level extension of the "Spotlight" app experience.
